				<div class="titBullet"></div>
				<h1><a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/solution-gently-killing-a-process">Solution: Gently killing a process</a></h1>
				<div class="metaRight">
				<img src="../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_user.png" alt="Author" /> <a href="../post/2007/01" title="Visit rechosen&#8217;s website" rel="external">rechosen</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_folder.png" alt="Category" /> <a href="solutions" title="View all posts in Solutions" rel="category tag">Solutions</a>	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="../wp-content/themes/colorbold/images/ico_tag.png" alt="Tags" />  <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/kill" rel="nofollow tag">kill</a>, <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/tag/process" rel="nofollow tag">process</a></div>
				<p>Sometimes you somehow can't quit a certain process, but you don't want to lose all unsaved data by killing it. You can then try giving it a SIGQUIT. This solution describes how. <a href="http://www.linuxtutorialblog.com/post/solution-gently-killing-a-process#more-22" class="more-link">read more</a></p>
 
